         <abstract>
            <p>We construct a two-goods inventory-theoretic money demand model and find that the model implies, in a monetary contraction, the decline in the prices of low cash-intensity goods, durables, or luxuries outpaces that of high cash-intensity goods, nondurables, or necessities. Using U.S. data, we show that our model's predictions are consistent with the data.</p>
         </abstract>
